I assume you want to call `empBean.convertToModel()` and not `empBean.getModel()`.

Please put some concrete code here how EmpBean inherits from BaseBean and how it is initialized. Then it should be easy to see.

Without that I can just take a wild guess:

 1. The `NPE` hints that you missed initializing BaseBean.a 
 2. Another reason might be &quot;shadowing&quot; if EmpBean has its own EmpBean.a:


If your class EmpBean looks like this:

    class EmpBean extends BaseBean {
        EmpAssembler a;
        EmpBean(EmpAssembler a) {
            this.a = a;
        }
	}
then EmpBean.a &quot;shadows&quot; BaseBean.a which means there are two instances of `a`:
`this.a` is initialized with some instance in the constructor but `super.a` is still `null`. And `BaseBean.convertToModel(...)` only knows the latter.
If this is your problem then you just have to remove `EmpAssembler a;`

Responding to you comment:
If constructor-injection is not an option, you might want to try annotation-based setter injection. Something like:

    @Autowired
	void setAssembler(EmpAssembler a) {
        this.a = a;
    }

