The alert from the state value is showing you the previous selected value because setState does not always happens instantly. Assuming that rest of the code is working correctly, try passing your alert call as a second parameter to the setState method.

Like this: 

````
handleDDLCommunityChange = (event) =&gt; {
alert(event.target.value);
/*this.setState({
selectedCommunity: event.target.value
});
alert(this.state[&#39;selectedCommunity&#39;].display);*/
this.setState({
selectedCommunity: event.target.value
},() =&gt; {alert(this.state[&#39;selectedCommunity&#39;].display)};
);
````

Regarding your first question, setState modifies the state asynchronously. 
So using this.state directly after calling setState won&#39;t give you the new state. 
Instead, setState takes a second parameter which is a function that will be called once the state change has been committed, like this:

       handleDDLCommunityChange = (event) =&gt; {
        alert(event.target.value);
        this.setState({
            selectedCommunity: event.target.value
        }, () =&gt; {
          alert(this.state[&#39;selectedCommunity&#39;].display);
        });
       }

Note: 

In the code you pasted you&#39;re adding string quotes when you shouldn&#39;t. You can think of the curly braces in JSX as &quot;break out of HTML mode and go to JavaScript&quot;. So when you want to bind a JS value to a HTML attribute it&#39;s enough to do:

    &lt;option key={community.value}&gt;

Where community is a JS variable in the current scope (inside your Render function, same as this)

For your other questions:


1) At the start of your render function you can check your conditions for if the button should be displayed or not and save it into a variable:

    const shouldShowButton = // Logic that checks

Then in your render you can do:

    &lt;button id=&quot;download&quot; styles={{ display: shouldShowButton ? &#39;block&#39; : &#39;none&#39; }} &gt;Download&lt;/button&gt;

The style attribute takes an object, hence the double curly braces. Another option is using https://www.npmjs.com/package/classnames.

2) In your handleDDLCommunityChange function you can use something like https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Fetch_API/Using_Fetch, like:

    fetch(/* endpointURL/?community= event.target.value /*).then( /* setState */)

And then use the value in state inside render to set the value for shouldShowButton

3) Assuming that you&#39;re saving the resulting list of communities in your state, that will trigger a re-render so you should be able to simply map over those items in state, the same way you do with your select. This is a key pattern in React, render a UI, respond to user interaction and store results of that interaction in state, and re-render.

