Custom converters are typically used at the field level to customer the mapping for a specific field pair within the overall mapping for a pair of classes. In this form, Dozer executes the rest of the mapping and calls your converter only for the field with the customer converter.

    &lt;mapping&gt;
        &lt;class-a&gt;ClassA&lt;/class-a&gt;
        &lt;class-b&gt;ClassB&lt;/class-b&gt;
        &lt;field custom-converter=&quot;CustomConverterType1&quot;&gt;
            &lt;a&gt;field1&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;b&gt;field1Prime&lt;/b&gt;
        &lt;/field&gt;
    &lt;/mapping&gt;
    &lt;mapping&gt;
        &lt;class-a&gt;ClassA&lt;/class-a&gt;
        &lt;class-b&gt;ClassC&lt;/class-b&gt;
        &lt;field custom-converter=&quot;CustomConverterType2&quot;&gt;
            &lt;a&gt;field1&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;b&gt;field1Prime&lt;/b&gt;
        &lt;/field&gt;
    &lt;/mapping&gt;

It is also possible to configure a custom converter at the type level in a way that the converter is responsible for the entire mapping. This must be done in the Dozer configuration, as opposed to the mapping. Note, the converter is responsible for the entire mapping in this case.

    &lt;configuration&gt;
        &lt;custom-converters&gt;
            &lt;converter type=&quot;CustomConverterType1&quot;&gt;
                &lt;class-a&gt;ClassA&lt;/class-a&gt;
                &lt;class-b&gt;ClassB&lt;/class-b&gt;
            &lt;/converter&gt;
            &lt;converter type=&quot;CustomConverterType2&quot;&gt;
                &lt;class-a&gt;ClassA&lt;/class-a&gt;
                &lt;class-b&gt;ClassC&lt;/class-b&gt;
            &lt;/converter&gt;
        &lt;/custom-converters&gt;
    &lt;/configuration&gt;

See the Dozer documentation for more information on custom converters.
https://dozermapper.github.io/user-guide.pdf

